Step 1: Dataset Summary & Exploration¶

The pickled data is a dictionary with 4 key/value pairs:

  • 'features' is a 4D array containing raw pixel data of the traffic sign images, (num examples, width, height, channels).
  • 'labels' is a 1D array containing the label/class id of the traffic sign. The file signnames.csv contains id -> name mappings for each id.
  • 'sizes' is a list containing tuples, (width, height) representing the original width and height the image.
  • 'coords' is a list containing tuples, (x1, y1, x2, y2) representing coordinates of a bounding box around the sign in the image. THESE COORDINATES ASSUME THE ORIGINAL IMAGE. THE PICKLED DATA CONTAINS RESIZED VERSIONS (32 by 32) OF THESE IMAGES

To solve the problem, i've added a quite simply image manipulation below, so the traffic-sign types with the lowest amount of images were take and slightly rotated and zoomed, to generate additional images based on the given once. For all given images of the type, i generate a slightly clockwise, anti-clockwise and just zoomed version of the image. Don't forget, that all available images have the exact same resolution of 32x32 pixels, thats why i resized them after rotate or zoomed (crop + resize)

In [6]:
# Rotate, Crops and resizes an image
# Rotation causes non given pixels (in corners) to appear black-colored,
# to avoid black-pixels, the image is cropped and then resized to its original size.
def rotate_image(img, angle=6, crop_pixels=(2,2)):
    # Work on a copy
    copy = np.copy(img)
    
    # Rotate image by given angle
    # Ref: https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.ndimage.rotate.html
    rotated = ndimage.rotate(copy, angle, reshape=False)
    
    # Remove outer pixels of the image
    cropped = rotated[crop_pixels[0]:-crop_pixels[0], crop_pixels[1]:-crop_pixels[1],:]
    return cv2.resize(cropped,(int(32),int(32)))

# Iterate through n datasets (traffic-sign-class) with the lowest amount of images
# and generate variations based on the given images
for i in range(0,10):
    # Count the amount of given traffic-sign images for each class
    unique_item, unique_count = np.unique(train_labels, return_counts=True)
    
    # Get traffic-sign-type (id) with the lowest amount of images from the dataset
    min_label = unique_count.argmin()
    
    # Get indices of all available images/labels for this traffic-sign-type
    min_label_indices = np.where(train_labels == min_label)[0]
    
    # Create lists to store the newly generated data
    own_created_images = []
    own_created_labels = []
    
    # Iterate through all existing images of this type
    for index in min_label_indices:
        
        # Get the given images from the dataset
        toCopy = X_train[index]
        
        # Create and append variations (zoomed & 2x rotated)
        own_created_images.append(rotate_image(toCopy, angle=-6)) # Rotate clockwise
        own_created_images.append(rotate_image(toCopy, angle=6))  # Rotate anti clockwise
        own_created_images.append(rotate_image(toCopy, angle=0))  # Just zoomed)
        
        # Append each label for variant
        own_created_labels.append(min_label)
        own_created_labels.append(min_label)
        own_created_labels.append(min_label)
        
    # Append new created images to existing list of images
    train_labels = np.append(train_labels, np.array(own_created_labels), axis=0)
    X_train = np.append(X_train, np.array(own_created_images), axis=0)
    
    # Print out the new shape of the train data/labels to see the new amount of data
    # and to check if the amount is equally sized, which is required
    print("X_train.shape", X_train.shape)
    print("train_labels.shape", train_labels.shape)

Pre-process the Data Set (normalization, grayscale, etc.)¶

Minimally, the image data should be normalized so that the data has mean zero and equal variance. For image data, (pixel - 128)/ 128 is a quick way to approximately normalize the data and can be used in this project.

Other pre-processing steps are optional. You can try different techniques to see if it improves performance.

Use the code cell (or multiple code cells, if necessary) to implement the first step of your project.

In [8]:
# Normalized value (range -0.5 - +0.5) within the 32x32x1 shape
def normalize_image(rgb_image):
    grayscaled = cv2.cvtColor(rgb_image, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
    
    # Use the cv2 equalizeHist function to equalize the histogram 
    # value on the image so the image is more balanced in brightness
    equ_hist = cv2.equalizeHist(grayscaled)
    
    # Convert value from 0-255 to scale from -0.5 - +0.5
    return ((equ_hist + -128) / 128).reshape(32,32,1)


# During my research on how to improve the image normalization i've discovered the usage of
# np.std (for standard derivation) and np.mean substraction in the following post on stackoverflow
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/45301648/normalize-the-validation-set-for-a-neural-network-in-keras
# I've tried this normalization which improved my accurancy for the training and validation data ~5%
def normalization_image_improved(rgb_image):
    grayscaled = cv2.cvtColor(rgb_image, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
    mean_substracted = grayscaled - np.mean(grayscaled)
    return (mean_substracted / np.std(mean_substracted)).reshape(32,32,1)
    

# Normalize each image given by the train-dataset
normalized_train = []
for rgb_image in X_train:

Model Architecture¶

In [9]:
# Iterate above the image pixel by pixel for each conv-layer
conv_strides = [1, 1, 1, 1]

# Max-pooling in done by a 2x2 square using a 2x2 stride.
pooling_kernel_size = [1, 2, 2, 1]
pooling_stride = [1, 2, 2, 1]

# Keep the random-weights close to 0.0
mu = 0.0
sigma = 0.1

# VALID padding - Does not add zeros to the side of the image. 
# On the other hand, reduces the W/H-dimension after each conv-layer
padding = 'VALID' 

# Implementation stronly inspired by LeNet 
# Ref: http://yann.lecun.com/exdb/lenet/
def Calculate(x):
    # Input is a X,32,32,1 - Dimensional image.
    # X is the batch-size
    # 32x32 the height/width
    # 1 - Color channel (grayscaled)

    
    # --- First conv-layer
    # 5x5 Kernel - Out = 28 x 28 x 8
    
    # Bias for first conv-layer
    bias_conv1 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(8))
    
    # Weights vor first conv-layer
    weight_conv1 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([5, 5, 1, 8], mean = mu, stddev = sigma)) # Width, Height, In-Depth, Out-Depth
    
    # Matrice multiplication within the weights and add biases
    conv1 = tf.nn.bias_add(tf.nn.conv2d(x, weight_conv1, conv_strides, padding), bias_conv1)
    
    # Activation function
    relu1 = tf.nn.relu(conv1)

    # Pooling. In = 28 x 28 x 8 - Out = 14 x 14 x 8.
    pooling1 = tf.nn.max_pool(relu1, pooling_kernel_size, pooling_stride, padding)
    
    
    # ---- Second conv-layer
    # 5x5 Kernel - Out = 10 x 10 x 24
    
    # Bias for second conv-layer
    bias_conv2 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(24))
    
    # Weights vor second conv-layer
    weight_conv2 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([5, 5, 8, 24], mean = mu, stddev = sigma)) # Width, Height, In-Depth, Out-Depth
    
    # Matrice multiplication within the weights and add biases
    conv2 = tf.nn.bias_add(tf.nn.conv2d(pooling1, weight_conv2, conv_strides, padding), bias_conv2)
    
    # Activation function
    relu2 = tf.nn.relu(conv2)

    # Pooling. Input = 10 x 10 x 24. Output = 5 x 5 x 24.
    pooling2 = tf.nn.max_pool(relu2, pooling_kernel_size, pooling_stride, padding)
    
    
    # --- Third conv layer
    # 1x1 Kernel - Out = 5 x 5 x 16
    
    # Bias for third conv-layer
    bias_conv3 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(16))
    
    # Weights vor first conv-layer
    weight_conv3 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([1, 1, 24, 16], mean = mu, stddev = sigma)) # Width, Height, In-Depth, Out-Depth
    
    # Matrice multiplication within the weights and add biases
    conv3 = tf.nn.bias_add(tf.nn.conv2d(pooling2, weight_conv3, conv_strides, padding), bias_conv3)
    
    # Activation.
    relu3 = tf.nn.relu(conv3)
    
    
    # --- Flat (Preparation for Conv-Layer -> Full-connected)
    
    # In = 5 x 5 x 16 -> Out = 400
    flat = flatten(relu3)
    
    # 1. Dropout to avoid overfitting.
    dropout = tf.nn.dropout(flat, keep_prob)

    # First fully connected layer - In 400 Out 160
    weight1 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([400, 160], mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    bias1 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(160))
    out1 = tf.add(tf.matmul(dropout, weight1), bias1)
    out1 = tf.nn.relu(out1)
    
    # 2. Dropout to avoid overfitting.
    dropout1 = tf.nn.dropout(out1, keep_prob)
    
    # Second fully connected layer - In 120 Out 84
    weight2 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([160, 129], mean = mu, stddev = sigma)) # Fully connected layer
    bias2 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(129))
    out2 = tf.add(tf.matmul(dropout1, weight2), bias2)
    out2 = tf.nn.relu(out2)
    
    # Third fully connected layer - In 84 Out 43 (Amount of traffic-sign types)
    weight3 = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([129, 43], mean = mu, stddev = sigma)) # Fully connected layer
    bias3 = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(43))
    out3 = tf.add(tf.matmul(out2, weight3), bias3)

    return out3

Train, Validate and Test the Model¶

A validation set can be used to assess how well the model is performing. A low accuracy on the training and validation sets imply underfitting. A high accuracy on the training set but low accuracy on the validation set implies overfitting.

# Constants
# EPOCHS     - Amount of round to iterate through all train_data
# BATCH_SIZE - Amount of images before doing the weights-adjustment
# LEARN_RATE - Factor for the weight-adjustment.
EPOCHS = 25
BATCH_SIZE = 64
LEARN_RATE = 0.0006

# Placeholder variable for neural network. 
# X = Batch of images date
# Y = Batch of expected results for given data in X
# keep_prob = Keep probability for dropouts
x = tf.placeholder(tf.float32,[None, 32, 32, 1])
y = tf.placeholder(tf.int32, (None))
keep_prob = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, None)
one_hot_y = tf.one_hot(y, 43)

logits = Calculate(x)
In [11]:
# Optimizer
# Network learning - Adjust weights based on AdamOptimizer
# using the cross_entropy which is caculated based on the delta
# between the predicted and the correct value.
cross_entropy = tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits(labels=one_hot_y, logits=logits)
loss_operation = tf.reduce_mean(cross_entropy)
optimizer = tf.train.AdamOptimizer(learning_rate = LEARN_RATE)
training_operation = optimizer.minimize(loss_operation)
In [12]:
# Check the accurancy of the model

# Get the correct predictions based on the predicted values of 
# the network (logits) and the expected values (one_hot_y)
correct_prediction = tf.equal(tf.argmax(logits, 1), tf.argmax(one_hot_y, 1))
accuracy_operation = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(correct_prediction, tf.float32))

# Evaluate the accurancy of the network based on the predicts vs the expected data
def evaluate(x_data, y_data, keep_probability=1.0):
    # Get amount of data to test
    num_examples = len(x_data)
    
    # Variable to save the accuranc for each batch-run
    total_accuracy = 0
    sess = tf.get_default_session()
    
    # Iterate through given dataset in multiple BATCHES
    for offset in range(0, num_examples, BATCH_SIZE):
        # Get batch of data from the total amount of given data to evaluate
        batch_x, batch_y = x_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE], y_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE]
        
        # Let the network calculate it's predictions based on the current batch and add the accurancy
        # for the current batch on total_accurancy_counter
        accuracy = sess.run(accuracy_operation, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y, keep_prob: keep_probability})
        total_accuracy += (accuracy * len(batch_x))
        
    # Get the mean value of accurancy for all given batches
    return total_accuracy / num_examples

# Neural network training

# To save the model after training
with tf.Session() as sess:
    # Initilize network variables (e.g. weights, biases)
    sess.run(tf.global_variables_initializer())
    
    # Get total amount of data to train with
    num_examples = len(x_train)
    
    print("Training...")
    print()
    
    # Store the accurancy for the train and validation data for visualization purpose
    accurancies_train = []
    accurancies_valid = []
    
    # Loop for the amount of given epochs
    for i in range(EPOCHS):
        # Log start-time for current epoch
        starttime = time.time()
        
        # Shuffle training-data before running the epoch (so the batches are different for each epoch)
        shuffled_x, shuffled_y = shuffle(x_train, y_train)
        
        # Get batch of data to train with
        for offset in range(0, num_examples, BATCH_SIZE):
            end = offset + BATCH_SIZE
            batch_x, batch_y = shuffled_x[offset:end], shuffled_y[offset:end]
            
            # Run network within the given batch of training-data with the given dropout-rate (0.4)
            # Dropout rate = 1 - keep_prop
            sess.run(training_operation, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y, keep_prob: 0.6})
        
        # Get the current accurancy for both the train and validation data
        # In this case without dropout
        training_accuracy = evaluate(x_train, y_train, 1.0)
        validation_accuracy = evaluate(x_valid, y_valid, 1.0)
        
        # Save the accurnacy for the epoch in the lists for all accurancies for visualization
        accurancies_train.append(training_accuracy)
        accurancies_valid.append(validation_accuracy)
        
        # Get end time of the epoch
        endtime = time.time()
        
        # Print out informations about the epoch (duration, accurancies)
        print("Finished EPOCH {}/{} (duration {:.1f} seconds) ...".format(i+1, EPOCHS, (endtime - starttime)))
        print("Validation Accuracy = {:.3f}".format(validation_accuracy))
        print("Training Accuracy   = {:.3f}".format(training_accuracy))
        print()
    
    saver.save(sess, './traffic_sign_classifier')
    print("Model saved")

Output Top 5 Softmax Probabilities For Each Image Found on the Web¶

For each of the new images, print out the model's softmax probabilities to show the certainty of the model's predictions (limit the output to the top 5 probabilities for each image). tf.nn.top_k could prove helpful here.

The example below demonstrates how tf.nn.top_k can be used to find the top k predictions for each image.

tf.nn.top_k will return the values and indices (class ids) of the top k predictions. So if k=3, for each sign, it'll return the 3 largest probabilities (out of a possible 43) and the correspoding class ids.

Take this numpy array as an example. The values in the array represent predictions. The array contains softmax probabilities for five candidate images with six possible classes. tf.nn.top_k is used to choose the three classes with the highest probability:

# (5, 6) array
a = np.array([[ 0.24879643,  0.07032244,  0.12641572,  0.34763842,  0.07893497,
         0.12789202],
       [ 0.28086119,  0.27569815,  0.08594638,  0.0178669 ,  0.18063401,
         0.15899337],
       [ 0.26076848,  0.23664738,  0.08020603,  0.07001922,  0.1134371 ,
         0.23892179],
       [ 0.11943333,  0.29198961,  0.02605103,  0.26234032,  0.1351348 ,
         0.16505091],
       [ 0.09561176,  0.34396535,  0.0643941 ,  0.16240774,  0.24206137,
         0.09155967]])

Running it through sess.run(tf.nn.top_k(tf.constant(a), k=3)) produces:

TopKV2(values=array([[ 0.34763842,  0.24879643,  0.12789202],
       [ 0.28086119,  0.27569815,  0.18063401],
       [ 0.26076848,  0.23892179,  0.23664738],
       [ 0.29198961,  0.26234032,  0.16505091],
       [ 0.34396535,  0.24206137,  0.16240774]]), indices=array([[3, 0, 5],
       [0, 1, 4],
       [0, 5, 1],
       [1, 3, 5],
       [1, 4, 3]], dtype=int32))

Looking just at the first row we get [ 0.34763842, 0.24879643, 0.12789202], you can confirm these are the 3 largest probabilities in a. You'll also notice [3, 0, 5] are the corresponding indices.

Step 4 (Optional): Visualize the Neural Network's State with Test Images¶

This Section is not required to complete but acts as an additional excersise for understaning the output of a neural network's weights. While neural networks can be a great learning device they are often referred to as a black box. We can understand what the weights of a neural network look like better by plotting their feature maps. After successfully training your neural network you can see what it's feature maps look like by plotting the output of the network's weight layers in response to a test stimuli image. From these plotted feature maps, it's possible to see what characteristics of an image the network finds interesting. For a sign, maybe the inner network feature maps react with high activation to the sign's boundary outline or to the contrast in the sign's painted symbol.

Provided for you below is the function code that allows you to get the visualization output of any tensorflow weight layer you want. The inputs to the function should be a stimuli image, one used during training or a new one you provided, and then the tensorflow variable name that represents the layer's state during the training process, for instance if you wanted to see what the LeNet lab's feature maps looked like for it's second convolutional layer you could enter conv2 as the tf_activation variable.

For an example of what feature map outputs look like, check out NVIDIA's results in their paper End-to-End Deep Learning for Self-Driving Cars in the section Visualization of internal CNN State. NVIDIA was able to show that their network's inner weights had high activations to road boundary lines by comparing feature maps from an image with a clear path to one without. Try experimenting with a similar test to show that your trained network's weights are looking for interesting features, whether it's looking at differences in feature maps from images with or without a sign, or even what feature maps look like in a trained network vs a completely untrained one on the same sign image.

In [20]:
### Visualize your network's feature maps here.
### Feel free to use as many code cells as needed.

# image_input: the test image being fed into the network to produce the feature maps
# tf_activation: should be a tf variable name used during your training procedure that represents the calculated state of a specific weight layer
# activation_min/max: can be used to view the activation contrast in more detail, by default matplot sets min and max to the actual min and max values of the output
# plt_num: used to plot out multiple different weight feature map sets on the same block, just extend the plt number for each new feature map entry

def outputFeatureMap(image_input, tf_activation, activation_min=-1, activation_max=-1 ,plt_num=1):
    # Here make sure to preprocess your image_input in a way your network expects
    # with size, normalization, ect if needed
    # image_input =
    # Note: x should be the same name as your network's tensorflow data placeholder variable
    # If you get an error tf_activation is not defined it may be having trouble accessing the variable from inside a function
    activation = tf_activation.eval(session=sess,feed_dict={x : image_input})
    featuremaps = activation.shape[3]
    plt.figure(plt_num, figsize=(15,15))
    for featuremap in range(featuremaps):
        plt.subplot(6,8, featuremap+1) # sets the number of feature maps to show on each row and column
        plt.title('FeatureMap ' + str(featuremap)) # displays the feature map number
        if activation_min != -1 & activation_max != -1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", vmin =activation_min, vmax=activation_max, cmap="gray")
        elif activation_max != -1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", vmax=activation_max, cmap="gray")
        elif activation_min !=-1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", vmin=activation_min, cmap="gray")
        else:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", cmap="gray")
